description: The "schools" table in the "california_schools" database contains comprehensive information about schools in California. It includes details such as the school's name, address, status, type, funding, grade levels offered and served, and contact information. The table also provides information about the school's charter status, geographical coordinates, and administrative details. Each row represents a unique school, identified by a primary key "CDSCode".

The "satscores" table in the "california_schools" database contains information about SAT scores in different schools across California. It includes details such as the school name, district, county, enrollment numbers, number of test takers, average scores in reading, math, and writing, and the number of test takers whose total SAT scores are 1500 or above. The primary key is the California Department Schools (cds) code, which also references the "CDSCode" in the "schools" table.

The 'frpm' table in the 'california_schools' database contains detailed information about various schools in California, including their codes, names, types, and academic year. It also provides data on student enrollment, free meal count, and Free or Reduced Price Meal (FRPM) count for both K-12 and ages 5-17 categories. Additional details about charter school status, funding type, and 2013-14 CALPADS Fall 1 Certification Status are also included.

The "ruling" table in the "card_games" database is designed to store information about specific rulings. Each row in the table represents a unique ruling, identified by a unique ID, and includes details such as the date of the ruling and a description about the ruling.

The 'set_transactions' table in the 'card_games' database is designed to keep track of specific card sets. Each row in the table represents a unique card set, identified by a unique 'id'. The table also stores information about the language of the card, the set code for the set, and the translation of the card.

The 'legalities' table in the 'card_games' database holds information about the legality of different play formats in card games. Each row represents a unique legality, identified by a unique ID, and includes the format of play and its status. The table also contains a 'uuid' column that links to the 'cards' table, providing information about the specific card associated with the legality.

The "cards" table in the "card_games" database contains detailed information about various cards used in card games. Each row represents a unique card, identified by a unique ID, and includes details such as the artist, name, availability, border color, color identity, mana cost, and many other characteristics of the card. The table also includes information about the card's availability in foil or non-foil versions, whether it's a promotional or reprint card, and links to purchase the card.

The "sets" table in the "card_games" database contains detailed information about various card sets. Each row represents a unique set, identified by an ID, and includes details such as the number of cards in the set, the set code, release date, and type of expansion. It also provides information about the set's availability in different formats (foil, non-foil, online, etc.), its identifiers on different platforms, and the breakdown of cards in a booster pack.

The 'foreign_data' table in the 'card_games' database stores information about card games in various foreign languages. Each row represents a unique card, identified by an 'id', and includes details such as the foreign flavor text, language, multiverse identifier, name, text ruling, and type of the card. The 'uuid' column is a foreign key that references the 'cards' table.

The "postLinks" table in the "codebase_community" database is designed to store information about the links between different posts. Each record in the table represents a link, identified by a unique post link id, and includes details such as the creation date of the link, the id of the post, the id of the related post, and the id of the link type.

The "postHistory" table in the "codebase_community" database is designed to store the history of posts made by users. It includes details such as the unique post history id, post id, post history type id, revision globally unique id, creation date, user id, detailed content of the post, comments, and the user's display name. This table is essential for tracking changes and revisions made to posts over time.

The "badges" table in the "codebase_community" database is designed to keep track of the badges earned by users. Each record in the table represents a badge, identified by a unique badge id, and includes information about the user who earned it (identified by a unique user id), the name of the badge, and the date the badge was obtained.

The "posts" table in the "codebase_community" database stores detailed information about each post made in the community. It includes data such as the post id, post type id, accepted answer id, creation date, score, view count, body content, owner user id, last activity date, title, tags, answer count, comment count, favorite count, last editor user id, last edit date, community owned date, parent post id, closed date, owner display name, and last editor display name. The table provides comprehensive insights into the popularity and activity of each post, including view counts and favorite counts, as well as the post's relationship to other posts through the parent post id.

The "users" table in the "codebase_community" database stores detailed information about each user in the community. It includes data such as user id, reputation, account creation date, display name, last access date, website URL, location, self-introduction, number of views, upvotes, downvotes, account id, age, and profile image URL. The reputation and age columns are particularly noteworthy, as they indicate the user's influence within the community and their age group respectively.

The 'tags' table in the 'codebase_community' database stores information about different tags used in the community. Each record in the table represents a unique tag, identified by an ID, and includes the tag name, the number of posts that contain this tag (indicating its popularity), and the IDs of the excerpt and wiki posts related to the tag. Some tags may not have associated excerpt or wiki posts.

The 'votes' table in the 'codebase_community' database is designed to record voting activities within the community. Each row represents a vote, with details including the vote ID, the ID of the post being voted on, the type of vote, the date the vote was created, the ID of the user who voted, and any bounty amount associated with the vote. The 'PostId' and 'UserId' columns reference the 'posts' and 'users' tables respectively.

The "comments" table in the "codebase_community" database stores information about user comments on posts. Each record includes the comment ID, the unique post ID it's associated with, a score rating from 0 to 100 indicating the positivity of the comment, the comment's text, its creation date, and details about the user who posted the comment, including their ID and display name.

The 'customers' table in the 'debit_card_specializing' database holds information about the customers. It contains three columns: 'CustomerID' which is a unique identifier for each customer, 'Segment' which indicates the client segment, and 'Currency' which specifies the currency used by the customer. The table is primarily keyed on 'CustomerID'.

The 'gasstations' table in the 'debit_card_specializing' database stores information about different gas stations. Each record in the table represents a unique gas station, identified by a 'GasStationID', and includes details about the chain it belongs to ('ChainID'), the country it's located in, and the segment of the chain. The segment could be 'Value for money', 'Premium', or 'Other'.

The 'products' table in the 'debit_card_specializing' database holds information about various products. It consists of two columns: 'ProductID' which is a unique identifier for each product and is the primary key, and 'Description' which provides a textual description of the product.

The 'yearmonth' table in the 'debit_card_specializing' database is designed to track the consumption of customers on a monthly basis. It contains three columns: 'CustomerID', 'Date', and 'Consumption'. The 'CustomerID' and 'Date' columns are used as a composite primary key, and 'CustomerID' is also a foreign key referencing the 'customers' table. The 'Consumption' column records the consumption amount.

The 'transactions_1k' table in the 'debit_card_specializing' database records transaction details of customers using debit cards at gas stations. Each row represents a unique transaction, identified by a TransactionID, and includes information such as the date and time of the transaction, customer ID, card ID, gas station ID, product ID, amount of product purchased, and the total price. The total price is calculated as the product of the amount and the price per unit.

The "Team_Attributes" table in the "european_football_2" database provides detailed information about the attributes of various football teams. It includes unique identifiers for the teams, the date of the record, and a range of attributes related to the team's playing style, such as build-up play speed, dribbling, passing, positioning, chance creation, and defence strategies. Each attribute is quantified and also classified into categories like 'Balanced', 'Normal', 'Organised', etc. based on the scores.

The "Player" table in the "european_football_2" database stores information about individual football players. Each row represents a player, identified by a unique id, and includes details such as the player's name, their API and FIFA API ids, birthday, height, and weight. The birthday column can be used to compare the ages of different players.

The "Match" table in the "european_football_2" database contains detailed information about individual football matches. It includes data about the teams involved, the season and stage of the match, the date, and specific details about the match such as goals scored, shots on and off goal, fouls committed, cards given, and ball possession. The table also contains foreign keys linking to the "Player" and "Team" tables, providing further context about the players and teams involved in each match.

The "League" table in the "european_football_2" database stores information about various football leagues. Each record in the table represents a league, identified by a unique ID, and includes the unique ID of the country where the league is based and the name of the league. The country ID is a foreign key that references the "country" table.

The "Country" table in the "european_football_2" database stores information about different countries. It consists of two columns: 'id' which is a unique identifier for each country, and 'name' which holds the name of the country. For instance, it includes countries like Belgium, England, and France.

The "Player_Attributes" table in the "european_football_2" database provides comprehensive data about football players' skills and attributes. It includes unique identifiers for each player, their overall rating, potential, preferred foot, work rates, and a wide range of skill scores such as crossing, finishing, dribbling, and goalkeeping abilities. Each attribute is scored between 0-100, calculated by FIFA, providing a detailed profile of each player's strengths and weaknesses.

The "Team" table in the "european_football_2" database stores information about various football teams. Each row represents a unique team, identified by a unique id, and includes details such as the team's API id, FIFA API id, long name, and short name.

The 'loan' table in the 'financial' database stores information about various loans. Each record includes the loan ID, the associated account ID, the date the loan was approved, the approved amount in US dollars, the loan duration in months, the monthly payments, and the repayment status. The status can indicate whether the contract is finished or running and if there have been any payment issues.

The 'client' table in the 'financial' database stores information about the bank's clients. Each row represents a unique client, identified by a unique 'client_id', and includes details such as the client's gender, birth date, and the ID of the district where their branch is located. The 'district_id' is a foreign key that references the 'district' table.

The 'district' table in the 'financial' database contains detailed information about different districts. It includes data such as the district name, region, municipality hierarchy, ratio of urban inhabitants, average salary, unemployment rates for 1995 and 1996, number of entrepreneurs per 1000 inhabitants, and the number of committed crimes for 1995 and 1996. The 'district_id' serves as the primary key for this table.

The 'trans' table in the 'financial' database stores information about various transactions. Each record includes details such as transaction id, account id, date of transaction, type of transaction (credit or withdrawal), mode of operation, amount of money involved in the transaction, and the balance after the transaction. The table also contains optional fields for the symbol, bank, and account related to the transaction.

The 'account' table in the 'financial' database holds information about various accounts. It includes details such as the account id, the location of the branch (district_id), the frequency of the account, and the creation date of the account. The account_id serves as the primary key, and the district_id is a foreign key referencing the district table.

The 'card' table in the 'financial' database stores information about credit cards. It includes details such as the card's unique ID, the associated disposition ID, the type of credit card (junior, classic, or gold), and the date the card was issued. The 'disp_id' column is a foreign key that references the 'disp' table.

The "order" table in the "financial" database is used to track individual financial transactions. Each row represents a unique order, identified by the "order_id", and includes details such as the account initiating the transaction ("account_id"), the recipient's bank and account ("bank_to" and "account_to"), the debited amount ("amount"), and the purpose of the payment ("k_symbol"). The "k_symbol" can indicate various types of payments such as insurance, household, leasing, or loan payments.

The 'disp' table in the 'financial' database is used to manage the relationship between clients and their accounts. It contains unique identifiers for each record (disp_id), the client (client_id), and the account (account_id), as well as the type of disposition (type) which can be 'OWNER', 'USER', or 'DISPONENT'. The type of disposition indicates the level of control a client has over an account, such as the ability to issue orders or apply for loans.

The 'circuits' table in the 'formula_1' database stores information about various racing circuits. Each record includes details such as a unique circuit ID, reference name, full name, location (city and country), geographical coordinates (latitude and longitude), and a URL for more information. The 'circuitId' serves as the primary key for the table.

The "status" table in the "formula_1" database is used to store different statuses that can be assigned to a race participant. It consists of two columns: "statusId", which is a unique identifier for each status, and "status", which contains the full name of the status such as 'Finished', 'Disqualified', or 'Accident'.

The "drivers" table in the "formula_1" database stores detailed information about Formula 1 drivers. Each record includes the driver's unique ID, reference name, number, abbreviated code, forename, surname, date of birth, nationality, and a URL to their introduction website. The "driverId" serves as the primary key for the table.

The "driverStandings" table in the "formula_1" database holds information about the standings of drivers in various races. Each record in the table represents a driver's performance in a race, identified by unique "driverStandingsId", and includes details such as the race and driver IDs, points acquired, position, and number of wins. The table has foreign key relationships with the "races" and "drivers" tables.

The 'races' table in the 'formula_1' database stores information about various Formula 1 races. Each row represents a unique race, identified by a 'raceId', and includes details such as the year the race took place, the round, the circuit Id, the name of the race, the date and time of the race, and a URL for more information about the race. The table has relationships with the 'seasons' and 'circuits' tables through the 'year' and 'circuitId' columns respectively.

The "constructors" table in the "formula_1" database holds information about the constructors involved in Formula 1 racing. Each row represents a constructor, identified by a unique constructorId, and provides details such as the constructor's reference name, full name, nationality, and a URL for more information. The table does not contain a column for wins.

The "constructorResults" table in the "formula_1" database holds information about the results of constructors in various races. Each row represents a unique constructor result, identified by the "constructorResultsId", and includes details such as the race and constructor IDs, the points earned, and the status of the constructor. The table has foreign key relationships with the "races" and "constructors" tables.

The "lapTimes" table in the "formula_1" database stores detailed information about each lap in a race. It includes the race and driver identification numbers, the lap number, the driver's position during that lap, the lap time in minutes and seconds, and the lap time in milliseconds. The table is linked to the "races" and "drivers" tables through the "raceId" and "driverId" columns respectively.

The "qualifying" table in the "formula_1" database holds information about the qualifying rounds of Formula 1 races. Each row represents a driver's performance in the qualifying rounds, with unique identifiers for the qualifying round, race, driver, and constructor. The table also includes the driver's number, position on the track, and times for the three qualifying rounds (Q1, Q2, Q3). The times for Q2 and Q3 are only recorded for the top 15 and top 10 drivers from the previous rounds, respectively.

The "pitStops" table in the "formula_1" database stores detailed information about each pit stop made during a race. It includes the race and driver identification numbers, the stop number, the lap number, the exact time of the stop, the duration of the stop in seconds, and the duration in milliseconds. The primary key is a combination of the raceId, driverId, and stop number, and there are foreign key relationships with the "races" and "drivers" tables.

The "seasons" table in the "formula_1" database stores information about different Formula One seasons. Each record in the table represents a unique season, identified by the year, and includes a URL that leads to a webpage with more information about that particular season. The year serves as the primary key for the table.

The "constructorStandings" table in the "formula_1" database holds information about the standings of different constructors in various races. Each record in the table is uniquely identified by the "constructorStandingsId". The table also includes details such as the race and constructor IDs, the points acquired in each race, the position or track of circuits, and the number of wins. The "raceId" and "constructorId" fields are foreign keys referencing the "races" and "constructors" tables respectively.

The "results" table in the "formula_1" database stores detailed information about the results of each race. It includes unique identifiers for the race, driver, and constructor, as well as specific details about the race such as the grid position, finishing position, points earned, number of laps, finish time, fastest lap time and speed. The table also includes a status ID, which provides additional information about the status of the race.

The "Income" table in the "student_club" database is designed to track the income of the club. It includes a unique identifier for each income record (income_id), the date the funds were received (date_received), the amount of funds in dollars (amount), the source of the funds (source), any additional details about the receipt of funds (notes), and a link to the member associated with the income (link_to_member). This table provides a comprehensive view of the club's financial inflows.

The "Budget" table in the "student_club" database is designed to track and manage the budget for various categories such as advertisement, food, parking, etc., for different events. Each entry in the table is uniquely identified by a 'budget_id' and is linked to a specific event. The table records the amount budgeted, spent, and remaining for each category, and also provides the status of the event (Closed, Open, Planning).

The "Zip_Code" table in the "student_club" database contains information about various ZIP codes in the United States. It includes the ZIP code itself, the type of ZIP code (Standard, PO Box, or Unique), the city, county, and state to which the ZIP code pertains, and the abbreviation of the state. This table can be used to identify the location details associated with a specific ZIP code.

The "Expense" table in the "student_club" database is designed to track and manage the club's expenses. It contains unique identifiers for each expense, a description of the expense, the date it was incurred, the cost in dollars, a boolean value indicating whether the expense was approved, and links to the member who incurred the expense and the corresponding budget record. This table is crucial for financial management and accountability within the club.

The "Member" table in the "student_club" database stores detailed information about each club member. It includes unique identifiers, personal details like first and last names, email, phone number, and zip code, as well as club-related details like the member's position and t-shirt size. It also contains a reference to the "Major" table through the "link_to_major" column, indicating the member's major.

The "Attendance" table in the "student_club" database is used to track the attendance of club members at various events. It contains two columns: "link_to_event", which is a unique identifier referencing the specific event attended in the Event table, and "link_to_member", which is a unique identifier referencing the member who attended the event in the Member table.

The "Event" table in the "student_club" database holds information about various events organized by the club. It includes details such as a unique event identifier, the event's name, date, type, notes, location, and its current status (whether it's in planning, open, or closed). This table serves as a comprehensive record of all past, present, and future events of the club.

The "Major" table in the "student_club" database is designed to store information about different majors. Each major is uniquely identified by a "major_id", and the table also includes the "major_name", the "department" that offers the major, and the "college" that houses the department. This table serves as a comprehensive guide to the various majors available in the institution.

The "gender" table in the "superhero" database is used to store the gender information of superheroes. It consists of two columns: "id", which is a unique identifier for each gender, and "gender", which specifies the gender of the superhero. The gender can be Male, Female, or N/A.

The 'superpower' table in the 'superhero' database is used to store information about various superpowers. It has two columns: 'id', which is a unique identifier for each superpower, and 'power_name', which stores the name of the superpower. For example, it includes superpowers like 'Agility', 'Accelerated Healing', and 'Lantern Power Ring'.

The 'publisher' table in the 'superhero' database is used to store information about different publishers. It has two columns: 'id', which is a unique identifier for each publisher, and 'publisher_name', which stores the name of the publisher. Some publishers may not have a name specified.

The "superhero" table in the "superhero" database stores detailed information about various superheroes. Each record in the table represents a unique superhero, identified by an ID, and includes details such as the superhero's name, full name, gender, eye color, hair color, skin color, race, publisher, alignment, height in centimeters, and weight in kilograms. The gender, eye color, hair color, skin color, race, publisher, and alignment are represented by IDs that reference other tables.

The "colour" table in the "superhero" database is used to store information about different colors associated with superheroes, such as their skin, eye, or hair color. Each entry in the table has a unique identifier "id" and a corresponding "colour" text field. For example, the color "Amber" is associated with the id "2".

The "attribute" table in the "superhero" database is designed to store the unique identifiers and names of various attributes that define a superhero's capabilities and characteristics. These attributes could range from physical traits like strength and speed to personal traits such as intelligence. Each attribute is uniquely identified by an 'id' and is described by the 'attribute_name'.

The 'hero_power' table in the 'superhero' database is a junction table that links heroes to their respective powers. It consists of two columns: 'hero_id', which corresponds to the ID of the hero in the 'superhero' table, and 'power_id', which corresponds to the ID of the power in the 'superpower' table. This table essentially maps the relationship between a superhero and their specific abilities used to fight crime and protect others.

The 'race' table in the 'superhero' database is used to store information about the different races or groups that a superhero can belong to. It consists of two columns: 'id', which is a unique identifier for each race, and 'race', which describes the specific group or race of the superhero. The 'race' column can contain values like 'Alien', 'Alpha', or even a '-' indicating an unknown or unspecified race.

The "alignment" table in the "superhero" database is used to categorize superheroes based on their moral and ethical stance. It consists of two columns: "id", which is a unique identifier for each alignment, and "alignment", which describes the overall attitude or behavior of a superhero. The alignment can be "Good", "Neutral", or "Bad", representing superheroes who are selfless and dedicated to justice, those who act based on their own moral code, and those who are selfish and manipulative, respectively.

The 'hero_attribute' table in the 'superhero' database stores the attributes of each superhero. Each row represents a specific attribute of a superhero, identified by 'hero_id', and the attribute's value. The 'attribute_id' corresponds to a specific attribute, and 'attribute_value' indicates the level of that attribute for the superhero. Higher attribute values suggest a superhero is more skilled or powerful in that particular area.

The "Laboratory" table in the "thrombosis_prediction" database stores detailed laboratory test results for patients. Each row represents a unique test result for a patient on a specific date, with the patient's ID and the date of the test serving as the primary key. The table includes a wide range of test results, such as levels of various proteins, enzymes, and blood cells, as well as results for specific tests related to rheumatoid factors and anti-bodies.

The "Patient" table in the "thrombosis_prediction" database stores information about patients, including their ID, sex, birthday, the first date their data was recorded, the date of their first hospital visit, whether they were admitted to the hospital or followed at the outpatient clinic, and their disease diagnosis. The table is primarily used to track patient data over time, with a particular focus on their hospital admission status and diagnosis.

The "Examination" table in the "thrombosis_prediction" database stores detailed medical examination data for patients. It includes information such as the date of examination, concentrations of various antibodies, diagnosis, coagulation measures, symptoms, and the degree of thrombosis. Each row corresponds to a unique patient examination, with the patient's ID linking to the "Patient" table.

The 'bond' table in the 'toxicology' database stores information about various bonds in different molecules. Each row represents a unique bond, identified by 'bond_id', which is associated with a specific molecule, identified by 'molecule_id'. The 'bond_type' column indicates the type of the bond, which can be a single, double, or triple bond.

The "molecule" table in the "toxicology" database stores information about different molecules. Each record in the table has a unique identifier "molecule_id" and a "label" indicating whether the molecule is carcinogenic or not, with "+" indicating carcinogenic and "-" indicating non-carcinogenic.

The 'atom' table in the 'toxicology' database stores information about individual atoms that make up various molecules. Each row represents a unique atom, identified by 'atom_id', and includes the molecule it belongs to, represented by 'molecule_id', and the type of element it is (such as carbon, chlorine, etc.). The 'molecule_id' column links to the 'molecule' table in the same database.

The "connected" table in the "toxicology" database stores information about the connections between atoms. Each row represents a bond between two atoms, identified by their respective atom IDs. The table also includes a bond ID, which represents the specific bond between the two atoms.
